<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06297275 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06297275 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Delaine Eastin; ... Assails cutbacks  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  MILPITAS; EDUCATION; ORGANIZATION; SCHOOL; MONEY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  For months, community leaders in Milpitas have been laying the groundwork fortheir foundation. Now, they're ready to build on it.;   The newly formedMilpitas Education Foundation hopes to raise money for small grants thatteachers can use in their classrooms. Foundations elsewhere in the Bay Areahave raised enough money to rescue troubled sports and music programs.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  East Extra  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MILPITAS SCHOOLS FUND TAKES OFF  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Milpitas  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;Because we're brand new our goals for this year aren't in the hundreds ofthousands (of dollars) that would allow you to help a full sports program,&quot;said Annell Spencer, the foundation's vice chairwoman.;   The goal for thisschool year is $40,000. &quot;We're looking more toward classroom grants that willdirectly affect the students in the classroom,&quot; she said.;   Spencer said thefoundation soon will send information to all parents in Milpitas, telling themof the foundation's goals. Associate membership costs $25.;   In addition toraising money for the classroom grants, the foundation plans to go into theMilpitas business community to seek donations of time, money or equipment.;  The business community is already represented on the foundation's board. PatCross of Komag, 7-Eleven owner Bob Livengood, insurance agent Dan Youngs andrancher Joe McCarthy are on the board. So is Assemblywoman Delaine Eastin,D-Union City, who represents Milpitas in the Assembly.;   Eastin, a formerteacher, gave a fiery speech to educators last month about the failure toinvest in children.;   &quot;The way I was raised, children shouldn't sacrifice foradults; adults should sacrifice for children,&quot; she said.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  RICH RAMIREZ, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911023  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  256  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, October 23, 199100297275,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>